{'relation': ['https://d-scholarship.pitt.edu/44383/'], 'title': ['Mechanistic Insights into Iron-Catalyzed Allenic C\u2060–H Functionalization'], 'creator': ['Palermo, Philip'], 'description': ['The mechanism for the iron-catalyzed C–H functionalization of simple monosubstituted allenes is investigated. In this report, we determined that the mechanism of this transformation involves a deprotonation causing the organoiron species to transform from a datively bound η2-allene complex to a neutral η1-propargyliron complex. This iron species acts as a nucleophile for in-situ generated electrophiles, performing a SE2’ type reaction resulting in a disubstituted allene. Herein, we additionally discuss the subtle differences in ligand design and the ramifications on various reaction yields through analysis of electronic properties and x-ray structure.'], 'date': ['2023-05-10'], 'type': ['University of Pittsburgh ETD', 'PeerReviewed'], 'format': ['application/pdf', 'application/zip'], 'language': ['en', 'en'], 'rights': [None, None], 'identifier': ['https://d-scholarship.pitt.edu/44383/20/Palermo%20-%20ETD%20-%202.pdf', 'https://d-scholarship.pitt.edu/44383/2/Further%20Supplementa%20Information.zip', "  Palermo, Philip  (2023) Mechanistic Insights into Iron-Catalyzed Allenic C\u2060–H Functionalization.  Master's Thesis, University of Pittsburgh.    (Unpublished)  "]}